    {
        "id": "strings_basics",
        "title": "Introduction to Strings",
        "description": "Learn what strings are and how to create them in JavaScript.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "**Strings** are sequences of characters wrapped in quotes. You can create strings using:\n\n* Single quotes: `'Hello'`\n* Double quotes: `\"Hello\"`\n* Template literals: `` `Hello` ``\n\nTemplate literals are special because they allow **variable interpolation** and **multiline strings**."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const a = 'Hello';\nconst b = \"Hello\";\nconst c = `Hello`;\nconsole.log(a, b, c);"
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// Create a variable named 'message' with value \"Welcome!\"\n// Log the variable to the console\n",
                "instructions": "Create a string variable named `message` containing \"Welcome!\" and log it using `console.log(message)`.",
                "validate": {
                    "requirements": [
                        {
                            "type": "declaration",
                            "kind": "const",
                            "name": "message",
                            "initValue": "Welcome!"
                        }
                    ],
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [],
                            "output": [
                                "Welcome!"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            },
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "Template literals allow embedding variables directly using `${}` syntax:\n\n```javascript\nconst name = \"Sam\";\nconsole.log(`Hi, ${name}!`);\n```"
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "Which of the following is NOT a valid way to create a string?",
                "options": [
                    "'Hi'",
                    "\"Hi\"",
                    "`Hi`",
                    "[(Hi)]"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 3
            },
            {
                "question": "Which type of quotes allow variable interpolation?",
                "options": [
                    "Single",
                    "Double",
                    "Template Literals"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 2
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "strings_length",
        "title": "Get the length of a string",
        "description": "Learn how to find out how many characters are in a string.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "In JavaScript, every string has a property called **`.length`**. This property tells you exactly how many characters are in the string, including spaces and special characters."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const message = \"Hello World\";\nconsole.log(message.length); // Output: 11"
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "const str = \"Hello\";\n// Try logging the length of str\nconsole.log(str.length);",
                "instructions": "This is a playground. Run the code to see the length of the string."
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'str' is hiddenly defined for you\n// Log the length of 'str'\n",
                "instructions": "Log the length of the variable `str` (which is already defined for you behind the scenes).",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "str"
                    ],
                    "patterns": {
                        "required": [
                            "\\.length"
                        ]
                    },
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "hello"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "5"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "A"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "1"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                " "
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "1"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "What property is used to get the character count of a string?",
                "options": [
