    {
        "id": "strings_access_char",
        "title": "Accessing Characters",
        "description": "Learn how to get characters from a string using indexing or charAt.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "Strings behave like arrays of characters. You can access characters using:\n\n* **Indexing**: `str[index]`\n* **Method**: `str.charAt(index)`\n\nRemember, indexing starts at **0**."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const word = \"Hello\";\nconsole.log(word[0]); // 'H'\nconsole.log(word.charAt(4)); // 'o'"
            },
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "You can combine indexing with `.length` to access the last character of any string: `str[str.length - 1]`."
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'str' is provided\n// Log the first character of 'str'\n",
                "instructions": "Log the **first** character of the string `str`.",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "str"
                    ],
                    "patterns": {
                        "required": [
                            "str\\[0\\]|str\\.charAt\\(0\\)"
                        ]
                    },
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "hello"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "h"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "A"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "A"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "What is 'dog'[2]?",
                "options": [
                    "d",
                    "o",
                    "g"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 2
            },
            {
                "question": "What does 'Cat'.charAt(1) return?",
                "options": [
                    "C",
                    "a",
                    "t"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "strings_concat",
        "title": "String Concatenation",
        "description": "Learn how to combine multiple strings.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "To combine strings, you can use the **addition operator (`+`)** or the built-in **`.concat()`** method. The `+` operator is the most common approach.\n\nTemplate literals (backticks) also implicitly concatenate when interpolating."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const part1 = \"Hello\";\nconst part2 = \"World\";\nconst result = part1 + \" \" + part2 + \"!\";\nconsole.log(result); // \"Hello World!\""
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'firstName' and 'lastName' are provided\n// Log the full name (e.g., \"John Doe\")\n",
                "instructions": "Concatenate `firstName`, a space, and `lastName` to form a full name and log it.",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "firstName",
                        "lastName"
                    ],
                    "patterns": {
                        "required": [
                            "\\+|\\.concat"
                        ]
                    },
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "John",
                                "Doe"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "John Doe"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "What is \"10\" + \"20\"?",
                "options": [
                    "30",
                    "\"1020\"",
                    "\"10+20\""
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "strings_search_index",
        "title": "Finding Substrings (indexOf)",
        "description": "Learn to find the position of a substring within a string.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "The **`.indexOf(value)`** method searches for a string and returns the **starting index** of the first occurrence.\n\n* If the substring is found, it returns the index (0 or greater).\n* If the substring is **not found**, it returns **`-1`**."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const sentence = \"The quick brown fox.\";\nconsole.log(sentence.indexOf(\"quick\")); // 4\nconsole.log(sentence.indexOf(\"z\")); // -1\nconsole.log(sentence.lastIndexOf(\"o\")); // 15 (finds the last one)"
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'str' is provided\n// Log the index of the first space character (' ')\n",
                "instructions": "Use `indexOf()` to find and log the index of the first space character in `str`.",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "str"
                    ],
                    "patterns": {
                        "required": [
                            "\\.indexOf\\(' '\\)"
                        ]
                    },
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "Hello World"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "5"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "JavaScript is fun"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "10"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "What is 'Cat'.indexOf('a')?",
                "options": [
                    "0",
                    "1",
                    "2",
                    "-1"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            },
            {
                "question": "What does .indexOf() return if the substring is not found?",
                "options": [
                    "0",
                    "null",
                    "undefined",
                    "-1"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 3
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "strings_slice_substring",
        "title": "Extracting Parts of a String",
        "description": "Learn how to extract parts of a string using slice and substring.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "`slice(start, end)` extracts part of a string from `start` index to `end` index (**end is excluded**).\n\n* `substring(start, end)` works similarly but does not support negative indexes.\n* `slice` **supports negative indexes** (counting backward from the end)."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const word = \"JavaScript\";\nconsole.log(word.slice(0, 4)); // 'Java'\nconsole.log(word.slice(4));    // 'Script'\nconsole.log(word.slice(-3));    // 'ipt' (using negative index)"
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'str' is provided (e.g., \"Hello World\")\n// Log the first word (words are separated by a space)\n",
                "instructions": "Use **`indexOf`** to find the position of the first space, then use **`slice`** (from index 0 to the space's index) to extract and log the first word from `str`.",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "str"
                    ],
                    "patterns": {
                        "required": [
                            "\\.slice",
                            "\\.indexOf"
                        ]
                    },
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "Hello World"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "Hello"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "Hi All"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "Hi"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "What is 'Hello'.slice(1, 4)?",
                "options": [
                    "Hel",
                    "ell",
                    "llo"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            },
            {
                "question": "Does slice support negative indexes?",
                "options": [
                    "Yes",
                    "No"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 0
            },
            {
                "question": "What is 'Apple'.slice(-3)?",
                "options": [
                    "ppl",
                    "ple",
                    "App"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "strings_uppercase",
        "title": "Convert to Uppercase",
        "description": "Learn how to convert text to capital letters.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "type": "theory",
                "content": "To convert a string to all capital letters, you can use the **`.toUpperCase()`** method.\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> This method returns a **new** string; it doesn't change the original one (strings are immutable)."
            },
            {
                "type": "snippet",
                "language": "javascript",
                "code": "const lower = \"hello\";\nconst upper = lower.toUpperCase();\nconsole.log(upper); // \"HELLO\""
            },
            {
                "type": "editor",
                "startingCode": "// 'str' is provided\n// Log the uppercase version of 'str'\n",
                "instructions": "Log the uppercase version of the variable `str`.",
                "validate": {
                    "parameters": [
                        "str"
                    ],
                    "requirements": [
                        {
                            "type": "methodCall",
                            "object": "str",
                            "method": "toUpperCase"
                        }
                    ],
                    "tests": [
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "hello"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "HELLO"
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "input": [
                                "World"
                            ],
                            "output": [
                                "WORLD"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "quiz": [
            {
                "question": "Does .toUpperCase() change the original string?",
                "options": [
                    "Yes",
                    "No",
                    "Sometimes"
                ],
                "answerIndex": 1
            }
        ]
    },
